 0039:     """
 0040:     A binary lookup tree of intervals.
 0041:     The intervals contained in the tree are represented using ``Interval(a, b, data)`` objects.
 0042:     Each such object represents a half-open interval ``[a, b)`` with optional data.
 0043: 
 0044:     Examples:
 0045:     ---------
 0046: 
 0047:     Initialize a blank tree::
 0048: 
 0049:         >>> tree = IntervalTree()
 0050:         >>> tree
 0051:         IntervalTree()
 0052: 
 0053:     Initialize a tree from an iterable set of Intervals in O(n * log n)::
 0054: 
 0055:         >>> tree = IntervalTree([Interval(-10, 10), Interval(-20.0, -10.0)])
 0056:         >>> tree
 0057:         IntervalTree([Interval(-20.0, -10.0), Interval(-10, 10)])
 0058:         >>> len(tree)
 0059:         2
 0060: 
 0061:     Note that this is a set, i.e. repeated intervals are ignored. However,
 0062:     Intervals with different data fields are regarded as different::
 0063: 
 0064:         >>> tree = IntervalTree([Interval(-10, 10), Interval(-10, 10), Interval(-10, 10, "x")])
 0065:         >>> tree
 0066:         IntervalTree([Interval(-10, 10), Interval(-10, 10, 'x')])
 0067:         >>> len(tree)
 0068:         2
 0069: 
 0070:     Insertions::
 0071:         >>> tree = IntervalTree()
 0072:         >>> tree[0:1] = "data"
 0073:         >>> tree.add(Interval(10, 20))
 0074:         >>> tree.addi(19.9, 20)
 0075:         >>> tree
 0076:         IntervalTree([Interval(0, 1, 'data'), Interval(10, 20), Interval(19.9, 20)])
 0077:         >>> tree.update([Interval(19.9, 20.1), Interval(20.1, 30)])
 0078:         >>> len(tree)
 0079:         5
 0080: 
 0081:         Inserting the same Interval twice does nothing::
 0082:             >>> tree = IntervalTree()
 0083:             >>> tree[-10:20] = "arbitrary data"
 0084:             >>> tree[-10:20] = None  # Note that this is also an insertion
 0085:             >>> tree
 0086:             IntervalTree([Interval(-10, 20), Interval(-10, 20, 'arbitrary data')])
 0087:             >>> tree[-10:20] = None  # This won't change anything
 0088:             >>> tree[-10:20] = "arbitrary data" # Neither will this
 0089:             >>> len(tree)
 0090:             2
 0091: 
 0092:     Deletions::
 0093:         >>> tree = IntervalTree(Interval(b, e) for b, e in [(-10, 10), (-20, -10), (10, 20)])
 0094:         >>> tree
 0095:         IntervalTree([Interval(-20, -10), Interval(-10, 10), Interval(10, 20)])
 0096:         >>> tree.remove(Interval(-10, 10))
 0097:         >>> tree
 0098:         IntervalTree([Interval(-20, -10), Interval(10, 20)])
 0099:         >>> tree.remove(Interval(-10, 10))
 0100:         Traceback (most recent call last):
 0101:         ...
 0102:         ValueError
 0103:         >>> tree.discard(Interval(-10, 10))  # Same as remove, but no exception on failure
 0104:         >>> tree
 0105:         IntervalTree([Interval(-20, -10), Interval(10, 20)])
 0106: 
 0107:     Delete intervals, overlapping a given point::
 0108: 
 0109:         >>> tree = IntervalTree([Interval(-1.1, 1.1), Interval(-0.5, 1.5), Interval(0.5, 1.7)])
 0110:         >>> tree.remove_overlap(1.1)
 0111:         >>> tree
 0112:         IntervalTree([Interval(-1.1, 1.1)])
 0113: 
 0114:     Delete intervals, overlapping an interval::
 0115: 
 0116:         >>> tree = IntervalTree([Interval(-1.1, 1.1), Interval(-0.5, 1.5), Interval(0.5, 1.7)])
 0117:         >>> tree.remove_overlap(0, 0.5)
 0118:         >>> tree
 0119:         IntervalTree([Interval(0.5, 1.7)])
 0120:         >>> tree.remove_overlap(1.7, 1.8)
 0121:         >>> tree
 0122:         IntervalTree([Interval(0.5, 1.7)])
 0123:         >>> tree.remove_overlap(1.6, 1.6)  # Null interval does nothing
 0124:         >>> tree
 0125:         IntervalTree([Interval(0.5, 1.7)])
 0126:         >>> tree.remove_overlap(1.6, 1.5)  # Ditto
 0127:         >>> tree
 0128:         IntervalTree([Interval(0.5, 1.7)])
 0129: 
 0130:     Delete intervals, enveloped in the range::
 0131: 
 0132:         >>> tree = IntervalTree([Interval(-1.1, 1.1), Interval(-0.5, 1.5), Interval(0.5, 1.7)])
 0133:         >>> tree.remove_envelop(-1.0, 1.5)
 0134:         >>> tree
 0135:         IntervalTree([Interval(-1.1, 1.1), Interval(0.5, 1.7)])
 0136:         >>> tree.remove_envelop(-1.1, 1.5)
 0137:         >>> tree
 0138:         IntervalTree([Interval(0.5, 1.7)])
 0139:         >>> tree.remove_envelop(0.5, 1.5)
 0140:         >>> tree
 0141:         IntervalTree([Interval(0.5, 1.7)])
 0142:         >>> tree.remove_envelop(0.5, 1.7)
 0143:         >>> tree
 0144:         IntervalTree()
 0145: 
 0146:     Point queries::
 0147: 
 0148:         >>> tree = IntervalTree([Interval(-1.1, 1.1), Interval(-0.5, 1.5), Interval(0.5, 1.7)])
 0149:         >>> assert tree[-1.1]   == set([Interval(-1.1, 1.1)])
 0150:         >>> assert tree.at(1.1) == set([Interval(-0.5, 1.5), Interval(0.5, 1.7)])   # Same as tree[1.1]
 0151:         >>> assert tree.at(1.5) == set([Interval(0.5, 1.7)])                        # Same as tree[1.5]
 0152: 
 0153:     Interval overlap queries
 0154: 
 0155:         >>> tree = IntervalTree([Interval(-1.1, 1.1), Interval(-0.5, 1.5), Interval(0.5, 1.7)])
 0156:         >>> assert tree.overlap(1.7, 1.8) == set()
 0157:         >>> assert tree.overlap(1.5, 1.8) == set([Interval(0.5, 1.7)])
 0158:         >>> assert tree[1.5:1.8] == set([Interval(0.5, 1.7)])                       # same as previous
 0159:         >>> assert tree.overlap(1.1, 1.8) == set([Interval(-0.5, 1.5), Interval(0.5, 1.7)])
 0160:         >>> assert tree[1.1:1.8] == set([Interval(-0.5, 1.5), Interval(0.5, 1.7)])  # same as previous
 0161: 
 0162:     Interval envelop queries::
 0163: 
 0164:         >>> tree = IntervalTree([Interval(-1.1, 1.1), Interval(-0.5, 1.5), Interval(0.5, 1.7)])
 0165:         >>> assert tree.envelop(-0.5, 0.5) == set()
 0166:         >>> assert tree.envelop(-0.5, 1.5) == set([Interval(-0.5, 1.5)])
 0167: 
 0168:     Membership queries::
 0169: 
 0170:         >>> tree = IntervalTree([Interval(-1.1, 1.1), Interval(-0.5, 1.5), Interval(0.5, 1.7)])
 0171:         >>> Interval(-0.5, 0.5) in tree
 0172:         False
 0173:         >>> Interval(-1.1, 1.1) in tree
 0174:         True
 0175:         >>> Interval(-1.1, 1.1, "x") in tree
 0176:         False
 0177:         >>> tree.overlaps(-1.1)
 0178:         True
 0179:         >>> tree.overlaps(1.7)
 0180:         False
 0181:         >>> tree.overlaps(1.7, 1.8)
 0182:         False
 0183:         >>> tree.overlaps(-1.2, -1.1)
 0184:         False
 0185:         >>> tree.overlaps(-1.2, -1.0)
 0186:         True
 0187: 
 0188:     Sizing::
 0189: 
 0190:         >>> tree = IntervalTree([Interval(-1.1, 1.1), Interval(-0.5, 1.5), Interval(0.5, 1.7)])
 0191:         >>> len(tree)
 0192:         3
 0193:         >>> tree.is_empty()
 0194:         False
 0195:         >>> IntervalTree().is_empty()
 0196:         True
 0197:         >>> not tree
 0198:         False
 0199:         >>> not IntervalTree()
 0200:         True
 0201:         >>> print(tree.begin())    # using print() because of floats in Python 2.6
 0202:         -1.1
 0203:         >>> print(tree.end())      # ditto
 0204:         1.7
 0205: 
 0206:     Iteration::
 0207: 
 0208:         >>> tree = IntervalTree([Interval(-11, 11), Interval(-5, 15), Interval(5, 17)])
 0209:         >>> [iv.begin for iv in sorted(tree)]
 0210:         [-11, -5, 5]
 0211:         >>> assert tree.items() == set([Interval(-5, 15), Interval(-11, 11), Interval(5, 17)])
 0212: 
 0213:     Copy- and typecasting, pickling::
 0214: 
 0215:         >>> tree0 = IntervalTree([Interval(0, 1, "x"), Interval(1, 2, ["x"])])
 0216:         >>> tree1 = IntervalTree(tree0)  # Shares Interval objects
 0217:         >>> tree2 = tree0.copy()         # Shallow copy (same as above, as Intervals are singletons)
 0218:         >>> import pickle
 0219:         >>> tree3 = pickle.loads(pickle.dumps(tree0))  # Deep copy
 0220:         >>> list(tree0[1])[0].data[0] = "y"  # affects shallow copies, but not deep copies
 0221:         >>> tree0
 0222:         IntervalTree([Interval(0, 1, 'x'), Interval(1, 2, ['y'])])
 0223:         >>> tree1
 0224:         IntervalTree([Interval(0, 1, 'x'), Interval(1, 2, ['y'])])
 0225:         >>> tree2

static char __pyx_doc_12intervaltree_12intervaltree_12IntervalTree_58merge_overlaps[] = "\n        Finds all intervals with overlapping ranges and merges them\n        into a single interval. If provided, uses data_reducer and\n        data_initializer with similar semantics to Python's built-in\n        reduce(reducer_func[, initializer]), as follows:\n\n        If data_reducer is set to a function, combines the data\n        fields of the Intervals with\n            current_reduced_data = data_reducer(current_reduced_data, new_data)\n        If data_reducer is None, the merged Interval's data\n        field will be set to None, ignoring all the data fields\n        of the merged Intervals.\n\n        On encountering the first Interval to merge, if\n        data_initializer is None (default), uses the first\n        Interval's data field as the first value for\n        current_reduced_data. If data_initializer is not None,\n        current_reduced_data is set to a shallow copy of\n        data_initializer created with copy.copy(data_initializer).\n\n        If strict is True (default), intervals are only merged if\n        their ranges actually overlap; adjacent, touching intervals\n        will not be merged. If strict is False, intervals are merged\n        even if they are only end-to-end adjacent.\n\n        Completes in O(n*logn) time.\n        ";

 0640:         """
 0641:         Finds all intervals with overlapping ranges and merges them
 0642:         into a single interval. If provided, uses data_reducer and
 0643:         data_initializer with similar semantics to Python's built-in
 0644:         reduce(reducer_func[, initializer]), as follows:
 0645: 
 0646:         If data_reducer is set to a function, combines the data
 0647:         fields of the Intervals with
 0648:             current_reduced_data = data_reducer(current_reduced_data, new_data)
 0649:         If data_reducer is None, the merged Interval's data
 0650:         field will be set to None, ignoring all the data fields
 0651:         of the merged Intervals.
 0652: 
 0653:         On encountering the first Interval to merge, if
 0654:         data_initializer is None (default), uses the first
 0655:         Interval's data field as the first value for
 0656:         current_reduced_data. If data_initializer is not None,
 0657:         current_reduced_data is set to a shallow copy of
 0658:         data_initializer created with copy.copy(data_initializer).
 0659: 
 0660:         If strict is True (default), intervals are only merged if
 0661:         their ranges actually overlap; adjacent, touching intervals
 0662:         will not be merged. If strict is False, intervals are merged
 0663:         even if they are only end-to-end adjacent.
 0664: 
 0665:         Completes in O(n*logn) time.
 0666:         """

If provided, uses data_reducer and\n        data_initializer with similar semantics to Python's built-in\n        reduce(reducer_func[, initializer]), as follows:\n\n        If data_reducer is set to a function, combines the data\n        fields of the Intervals with\n            current_reduced_data = data_reducer(current_reduced_data, new_data)\n        If data_reducer is None, the merged Interval's data\n        field will be set to None, ignoring all the data fields\n        of the merged Intervals.\n\n        On encountering the first Interval to merge, if\n        data_initializer is None (default), uses the first\n        Interval's data field as the first value for\n        current_reduced_data. static char __pyx_doc_12intervaltree_12intervaltree_12IntervalTree_62merge_neighbors[] = "\n        Finds all adjacent intervals with range terminals less than or equal to\n        the given distance and merges them into a single interval. If provided,\n        uses data_reducer and data_initializer with similar semantics to\n        Python's built-in reduce(reducer_func[, initializer]), as follows:\n\n        If data_reducer is set to a function, combines the data\n        fields of the Intervals with\n            current_reduced_data = data_reducer(current_reduced_data, new_data)\n        If data_reducer is None, the merged Interval's data\n        field will be set to None, ignoring all the data fields\n        of the merged Intervals.\n\n        On encountering the first Interval to merge, if\n        data_initializer is None (default), uses the first\n        Interval's data field as the first value for\n        current_reduced_data. If data_initializer is not None,\n        current_reduced_data is set to a shallow copy of\n        data_initiazer created with\n            copy.copy(data_initializer).\n\n        If strict is True (default), only discrete intervals are merged if\n        their ranges are within the given distance; overlapping intervals\n        will not be merged. If strict is False, both neighbors and overlapping\n        intervals are merged.\n\n        Completes in O(n*logn) time.\n        ";
